      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay i get the sock thing but it's still a bit weird lol. what's the actual term for that \"instant\" connection part? i think i heard something about \"spooky action\" or something like that in class. can you explain what that specifically means?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, you're thinking of the term \"spooky action at a distance,\" coined by Albert Einstein, who was quite skeptical about this phenomenon. He called it \"spooky\" because it seemed to defy the very fabric of classical physics, which is like expecting a regular sock to have magical powers. In quantum entanglement, when two particles become entangled, their states are so deeply connected that measuring one particle's state will instantly determine the state of the other, even if they're light-years apart. This \"spooky\" connection happens faster than the speed of light, which is why Einstein was puzzled and even proposed the EPR paradox to challenge the idea. It's like having two magical twin socks that always match perfectly, no matter how far apart they are, and doing so instantaneously. This \"spooky\" action is a fundamental aspect of quantum mechanics, and it's one of the reasons why quantum entanglement is such a fascinating and mysterious phenomenon.",
